# Structured Resonant Coupling (SRC)
## Temporal Coupling Framework for Reactive Systems

This repository introduces a testable framework for improving energy coupling efficiency in reactive systems through temporal excitation structuring and passive phase control.

The approach does not introduce new physical principles. It operates within classical electromagnetic and electrochemical theory.

## Core Idea

Instead of optimizing only frequency and amplitude, SRC treats the following as primary variables:

- Temporal structure of excitation (Δt)
- Phase relationship between voltage and current (Δφ)
- Passive feedback shaping (RLC-based)

The hypothesis is that improved temporal alignment between excitation and system dynamics can reduce losses and stabilize operation.

## Scope

This framework is intended for:

- Electrochemical systems (e.g. electrolysis)
- Dielectric and relaxation-dominated media
- Plasma and transient field systems

## What this is NOT

- Not a new energy source
- Not a violation of thermodynamics
- Not a claim of energy amplification

## Goal

To test whether time-structured excitation improves:

- Phase stability
- Impedance consistency
- Effective energy coupling

## Status

Conceptual + experimental framework  
Open for validation, critique and replication

This framework is intentionally minimal and focuses on testability rather than completeness.
Independent replication is explicitly encouraged.
